Agt: Agreement on the Roadmap to a Peaceful and Democratic end of the Transitional Period of the Agreement on the Resolution of the Conflict in the Republic of South Sudan (R- ARCSS).
OthAgr:
page 2,
1.1 The Revitalized Agreement on the Resolution of the Conflict in the Republic of South Sudan (R-ARCSS) was concluded and signed on the 12h September 2018 and was scheduled to end after a total of forty-four (44) months: eight (8) months of a Pre-Transitional Period and thirty-six (36) months of a Transitional Period.

1.2. The schedule for the implementation of the provisions of the Agreement was not met due to a number of genuine challenges. Thus, the 8-month Pre- Transition Period started on 12" September 2018, and ended on 12" May 2019 without the establishment of the R-TGoNU as per article 1.1.2 of the R-ARCSS.

1.3 If the R-TGoNU was established by 12" May 2019, elections would have had to be carried out as from 12" March 2022, two (2) months before the end of the transitional period and the elected government established would have had to be formed by 12"' May 2022.

page 2 - 3,
1.7 The purpose of this report is to analyze the status of the R-ARCSS implementation, assess the possibility of starting the process of conducting elections from 22d December 2022, or propose an alternative timetable, a Road Map, for the parties to the Agreement to consider.

2. The Status of Implementation

2.1 Chapter-1 (Annex-1, Items 1 to 13): This Chapter of the R-ARCSS comprises twenty (20) Articles and two-hundred and eighty-three (283) sub- articles/Actions.

(i) The 283 activities are grouped into thirty-five (35) strategic objectives/actions, contained within the 20 Articles of the R-ARCSS Implementation Matrix (Pages 86-92), which all must be carried out.

page 3,
(iv) Article 1.20.1 on review of the Political Parties Act 2022 have to be reviewed to conform to the permanent constitution of the Republic of South Sudan and adoption by the constituent assembly prior to its dissolution.

page 4,
(ii) Article 1.4.3.1 on dissemination (Annex-3, Items 1 to 7) of the Revitalized ARCSS to South Sudanese people inside the country, in different cities and refugee camps in neighboring countries and generally in the diaspora, so that the people can understand, support and own it.

(iii) Article 1.4.3.3 on National Healing and Reconciliation Process.

(iv) Article 1.20 (inclusive of sub-articles/activities 1.20.2 to 1.20.12) on National Elections, Pre-election (Annex-2a Items 1 to 9), Elections and Post-Elections Annex-2b, Items 1 to 5).

2.2 Chapter-2 (Annex-4, items 1 to 7): The Permanent Ceasefire and Transitional Security Arrangements comprises five (5) Articles and one-hundred fourteen (114) sub-articles/Actions.

The one-hundred and fourteen (114) actions are grouped into 37 strategic objectives/actions, which are to be implemented as outlined in the R-ARCSS Implementation Matrix (Pages 93-98).

page 5,
2.3 Humanitarian Assistance and Reconstruction Chapter-3 (Annex-5, Items 19): This Chapter of the R-ARCSS comprises twenty-nine (29) actions. The twenty-nine (29) activities in R-ARCSS Implementation Matrix (pages 99-103) are to be carried out.

page 6,
(ii) Article 3.1.2.5 on reviewing the 2016 NGO Act as per international best practice.

page 6,
2.4 Chapter 4; Resource, Economic and Financial Management (Annex-6 Items 1 to 66): This Chapter of the R-ARCSS comprises of sixteen (16) Articles and one-hundred forty-five activities all of which must be executed.

page 8,
(i) The Revitalized Agreement on the Resolution of the Conflict in the Republic of South Sudan (R-ARCSS) does not provide critical timelines neither for the Permanent Constitution Making Process nor the Elections.

page 9,
(v) The objective is to ensure the full and peaceful end of the R-ARCSS with elections held and a democratically elected government for the Republic of South Sudan installed.

page 9,
(i) The review of the new National Elections Act to conform with the permanent constitution upon its ratification by the constituent assembly by the 30th of August, 2023.

Page 9,
(iii) The enactment of the Political Parties Act, 2022, on the establishment of the Political Parties, their registration and the establishment of the Political Parties Council if impacted upon by the permanent constitution.

page 11,
4.2 The meeting resolved to extend the transitional period of the R-ARCSS and directed the High-Level Standing Committee to receive the contributions of the other parties to the Agreement and incorporate them into the President's Roadmap proposal.
...
4.5 The harmonized Roadmap was re-submitted to a second extended meeting of the Presidency in which article 8.4 of the R-ARCSS was evoked to approve the amendment by extending the transition period from 22d February 2023, to 22nd February, 2025, with elections held in December, 2024. In that regard the extended meeting of the Parties:

page 12,
(iv) Calls upon RJMEC, IGAD, AU, all the Parties signatory to the R-ARCSS, all Stakeholders, Guarantors and International Partners to support the roadmap morally, politically, diplomatically and financially.

OthAgr:
Page 2, 6. Further noted with concern
the apparent lack of collegiality and harmony in the implementation and respect of the provisions of revised Marial-Bai agreement on cattle seasonal movement.

7. Alarmed by the continued carry of guns by an authorized person which is in violation of the provisions of Marial-Bai agreement and tri-state peace conference resolutions that is breeding mistrust and mutual suspicion among the communities, urges the authorities from both states to find an alternative mechanisms of removing guns out in the hands of civilians.

8. Called on governments in Tonj and Wau to facilitate the formation of the special mobile court as contained in article 11 of the tri-state peace conference resolutions of July 2019 to trial all the crimes committed during the previous and recent conflicts to avoid further revenge.

III.    The present document will be governed by the following agreements and protocols:
•    Agreement on the International Component and Accompaniment to the Peace Dialogue Table between the National Government and the Central General Staff of the FARC-EP.
•    Protocol of Rules and Commitments of the Bilateral, Temporary Ceasefire of a National character with Territorial Impact (CFBTNT).

•    Protocol for the Functioning of the Peace Dialogues Table.
•    Protocol for the Security and Protection of the members of MVMV.
•    Protocol for Transfers of Representatives of the Central General Staff of the FARC - EP, during the stages agreed by the parties.
•    Security Protocol for the Central General Staff of the FARC-EP and places where it is present
•    Protocol for the Participation and Social Oversight of the Population, their Communities and Organisations.
•    Communications protocol.
•    Protocol for the Evaluation, Extension or Suspension of the Bilateral and Temporary Ceasefire of National character and Territorial Impact (CFBTNT).
•    Pedagogic Protocol of the present Agreement and its protocols.
•    Other protocols and agreements of immediate application that are deemed necessary.
*Glossary of the Bilateral and Temporal Ceasefire of a National character with Territorial impact (CFBTNT).

OthAgr:
Page 2, Preamble:

... AWARE ... that the ongoing, pending programs in Revitalized Agreement on the Resolution of the Conflict in the Republic of South Sudan (R-ARCSS), and newly established programs in the Tumaini Consensus, shall provide the framework for peacebuilding and democratization in South Sudan;

Page 3, Preamble: 

... PERSUADED that the envisaged reforms, democratic transition, and changes towards a better South Sudan shall be achieved through a comprehensive and all-inclusive Tumaini Consensus and R-ARCSS

Page 9, 3. Protocol on Trust and Confidence-Building Measures:
		
THAT the Parties and Stakeholders, as a gesture of their commitment to the Tumaini Initiative, create a conducive atmosphere for the implementation of the Tumaini Consensus and R-ARCSS that will lead to the adoption of a Permanent Constitution for the Republic of South Sudan, agree to the immediate implementation of the following measures after the signing of the Tumaini Consensus:

... 

3.2 Expedite the repeal of Sections 54, 55 and 57 of the National Security Act 2014 so as to conform with the provisions of the Constitution, R-ARCSS and the Tumaini Consensus before the commencement of the implementation of the Tumaini Consensus;

Page 11, 4. Protocol on Permanent Ceasefire, Security Arrangements and Reforms:
		
THAT the Parties recommit to the Cessation of Hostilities Agreement (COHA) (2017), and commit to a permanent ceasefire agreement that shall be agreed in the Tumaini Consensus.

...

Page 14, 4.2.2 The functions of the JDSB shall be to:

4.2.2.2 Restructure and unify the army and other organized forces in accordance with the provisions of R-ARCSS and the Tumaini Consensus

Page 19, 6.1 Internal Guarantors:

... 6.1.2.4 Receive reports from all mechanisms established under the R-ARCSS as amended and the Tumaini Consensus;

OthAgr:
Page 1, Paragraph 2: "The participation spaces defined in the Participation Agreement must follow a prior plan that sequentially involves all the activities of the before (preparation), during (development of the spaces) and after (follow-up) each meeting scenario in an agenda agreed by the parties that contains at least the following elements:

a. The objective of each space should be defined in advance and describe the minimum results that are intended to be achieved

b. The venue for the event should be selected according to the chosen scenario and participation format, in all cases taking into account the participants, access, security, risks, among other factors considered necessary.

c. Logistical and administrative aspects must be guaranteed in the different participation spaces, including the necessary resources for logistics, material, technical and human means. The communities and their organisations may, in a concerted manner, provide support for the execution of guarantees for the spaces for participation convened by the MDP. The office of the Peace Commissioner Advisor will allocate the necessary resources to achieve the objectives of each event. The Peace Dialogues Table may have other sources of funding

d. Formal invitations issued by the MDP must be sent well in advance, ensuring compliance with the administrative procedures required for the participation of communities and institutional representatives. The coordinators of the parties will define who signs the invitations and the method of distributing them."
